english:
  title: The Biography of Kong Fang
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Kong Fang, whose courtesy name was Guan-zhi, descended from ancestors who once hid themselves on Shouyang Mountain, dwelling in caverns, never venturing forth to serve the world. In the age of the Yellow Emperor, he was first brought into use, though his nature was rigid and unyielding, poorly refined by worldly affairs. When the Emperor summoned a physiognomist to examine him, the master gazed long and said: "Though this mountain-born material seems crude and unworkable, should Your Majesty allow it to be tempered in the furnace and hammer of creation's forge, scraped clean and polished bright, its true nature would gradually reveal itself. A sage uses men as instruments; I humbly beseech you not to cast him aside like stubborn bronze." Thus Kong Fang became known to the world.

    Later, fleeing turmoil, he removed to the charcoal markets by the river and made his home there. His father, Quan, was Grand Steward under the Zhou, overseeing the state's revenues. Kong Fang himself possessed a nature round without and angular within, skilled at adapting to circumstance. He served under the Han as Honglu Qing. At that time King Wu of Wu grew arrogant and presumptuous in his power, and Kong Fang attached himself to him for great profit. In the time of Emperor Wu, when the realm grew impoverished and the imperial treasury emptied, the Emperor, troubled, appointed Kong Fang as Marquis of Enriching the People. Together with his associate Jin, Commissioner of Salt and Iron, Kong Fang stood in court, and Jin always called him elder brother, never using his name.

    Kong Fang's nature was greedy and corrupt, devoid of shame. Now managing the state's finances, he delighted in the art of balancing principal and interest, believing that enriching the nation need not rely solely on the craftsman's forge, but rather he could contend with the people for even the smallest profit. He depressed grain prices and raised the value of money, causing the people to abandon agriculture for commerce, bringing harm to farming. Though many remonstrators submitted memorials against him, the Emperor did not listen. Kong Fang moreover insinuated himself cleverly with the powerful, visiting their gates, peddling influence and selling offices, with promotions and demotions falling within his palm. Many nobles bent their principles in serving him. He accumulated grain and gathered bribes until documents piled like mountains, beyond counting. In his dealings with people and things, he made no distinction between worthy and base—any merchant or trader enriched by wealth became his associate, thus was born the market-place friendship.

    At times he consorted with street ruffians, spending his days at dice and cards, yet he was rather fond of keeping his word. Thus people of the age said: "One word from Kong Fang weighs as much as a hundred catties of gold." When Emperor Yuan ascended the throne, Gong Yu submitted a memorial saying: "Kong Fang has long managed arduous duties yet understood not the root of agriculture. He merely promotes mercantile profit, gnawing at the state and harming the people, impoverishing both public and private coffers. Moreover, bribes run rampant and solicitation proceeds openly—this is the clear warning of the Changes: 'When one carries and also rides, robbers come.' I humbly request his dismissal to chastise avarice."

    At that time, officials versed in the Gongyang school, fearing military supplies would prove insufficient and wishing to establish border policies, opposed Kong Fang's methods and supported the memorial. The Emperor heeded this, and Kong Fang was thus stripped of office. He said to his disciples: "Of late I served the Emperor alone, wielding transformative power over the realm, intending only that the state's resources should suffice and the people's wealth flourish. Yet for trivial failings I am now cast aside. Whether I rise or fall, I gain nothing and lose nothing. Fortunate that my remaining breath still flickers like gossamer thread. If I keep silent, content merely to preserve myself and depart, drifting like duckweed back to my estates by the Jianghuai, casting my lines by the creek, catching fish to buy wine, floating among merchants and sea traders on wine boats—this suffices to end my days. What care I for a thousand bushels of salary or the feasts of five tripods? Yet methinks my arts have endured long and shall rise again."

    He Xiao of the Jin dynasty heard his reputation and took pleasure in him, accumulating great wealth through his methods, until love became obsession. Thus Lu Bao composed his treatise condemning this, seeking to reform such corrupted customs. Only Ruan Xianzi, being free-spirited and disdaining vulgar pursuits, wandered with Kong Fang's followers, and at wine shops would drink without restraint. Wang Yifu never spoke Kong Fang's name aloud, referring to him only as "that thing," so despised was he by those of pure reputation.

    When the Tang arose, Liu Yan became Commissioner of Finances. Finding state resources insufficient, he petitioned the throne to restore Kong Fang's methods for the empire's benefit—his words appear in the Records of Commerce. By then Kong Fang had long been dead, yet his scattered disciples were sought out and restored to service. Thus his methods flourished greatly during the Kaiyuan and Tianbao eras. The throne even posthumously granted him the rank of Minister of Court Deliberations and Junior Minister of the Imperial Treasury.

    During the Northern Song under Emperor Shenzong, Wang Anshi seized power and drew Lü Hui-jing to govern with him, establishing the Green Sprout Law. At this time the realm grew troubled and impoverished. Su Shi argued vehemently against its abuses, seeking to abolish it entirely, but was instead ensnared and banished. Thereafter, court officials dared not speak. When Sima Guang entered as Prime Minister, he petitioned to abolish the law and recommended Su Shi for promotion, whereupon Kong Fang's followers gradually weakened and never flourished again.

    Kong Fang's son, Lun, was despised for his frivolity. Later he became Minister of the Imperial Waterworks but was executed when his corruption was exposed. The historian remarks: "A vassal who harbors divided loyalty and grasps uncounted favor from his lord, when fortune smiles and the furnace of transformation roars, should repay that grace by promoting benefit and removing harm. Yet Kong Fang aided Wu's usurpation and established his private faction—he violated the principle that the loyal serve without foreign alliances.

    "When Kong Fang died, his followers rose again under the Northern Song, fawning upon those in power and slandering the righteous. Though the span of fortune lies in that mysterious realm beyond sight, had Emperor Yuan but heeded Gong Yu's counsel and purged them utterly in a single day, later calamities might have been prevented. Instead, merely restraining them, he let their poison seep through the ages. Thus do those whose words precede events often lament that they are not believed."
  footnotes:
    - 'Shouyang Mountain: A legendary mountain where virtuous recluses once withdrew from the world, evoking the ideal of integrity and refusal to serve corrupting powers.'
    - 'The furnace and hammer of creation: A metaphor for the transformative power of proper governance and cultivation, suggesting that even rough material can be refined into something valuable.'
    - Kong Fang's physical description—round outside, angular within—is a pun on coins (圓外方內), foreshadowing his nature as an instrument of commerce and fiscal power.
    - 'Market-place friendship (市井交): Friendship based on mutual profit rather than virtue, a concept Confucian scholars viewed as corrupting true relationship.'
    - 'The Changes (大易): Reference to the I Ching, with the warning about carrying and riding being a metaphor for overreaching ambition inviting disaster.'
    - 'The Green Sprout Law (青苗法): Wang Anshi''s controversial policy of state-issued loans to farmers during planting season, which his critics argued harmed the common people.'
    - Kong Fang's final disappearance into commerce, combined with the historical echo of his methods resurging, suggests the cyclical and persistent nature of corruption driven by material greed.
